Turkey is expanding diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey tried to enter the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern part of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps in Asia, is one of the most beautiful relics of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that’s what tourist guides tell you.
The building is riding between the ends of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking at the world like some German provincial municipalities.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is decadent.
But once inside the office ticket from the ceiling from time to time, there is no doubt about the size of the enterprise of what was the most western passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a retarded imperialist, wanted to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East through this railroad that ran in Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany’s imperial ambitions drowned during the First World War.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
The relative isolation from the surrounding region, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has passed
British and dominant forces advanced out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for Hyderpasha station as well.
In 1917 a train of ammunition exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was a sabotage.
Since then it has slowly gone into disguise, largely outperformed by history.
But today, this railroad departure for Anatolia and all the points to the east, serve - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's growing diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party – the AKP – has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has passed.
Now there is a new policy of commitment.
Notably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To estimate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded the carriageway to the Turkish capital Ankara, to visit one of the AKP’s leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MEP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning – about ten and a half hours later – after a run of swamps along the tracks that produced the cadences from the ancient world of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital – proposed as a new city for a secular state intended to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in Turkish consensus.
He suggested some suspicions in the West, most notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern stone and steel structure - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by built-medium shopping centers and power pastry, where managers in complete business - both men and women - meet up against them first.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a center-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Complete, tie, I'm sure he also had a Blackberry.
“The purpose of the foreign policy party now is to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbors.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he says.
Turkey has been cut off from its interior.
Today it has to look east and west at the same time.
It was not the case of one or the other.
They must be both.
"But surely at some point," I ask, "will Turkey be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he says, "doesn't want to face that choice."
Then he points out a point that almost all of those with whom I have spoken here have spoken in memory: the ties of not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are for Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, the whole of Europe can metaphorically travel those railway lines east through Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha station, after another white night, I think of those two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who had looked at this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to find that Europe's Middle Eastern ambitions can now be largely in Turkey's hands.
