The "bee car" to avoid collisions
As part of the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, and especially by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking the flight of bees, for example, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers from Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is an extension of Nissan’s four-area Security Shield.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the vehicle of the manufacturer.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal oval shaped space that is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important thing is the composite eyes of bees, able to see in all directions with an angle of more than 300 degrees, and that allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To recreate this visual feature, engineers developed what they called a Laser Range Finder.
This mechanism detects the obstacles facing the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object, and sends a signal to a edge microprocessor that immediately prevents collision.
"As soon as he detects an obstacle, the small robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at a rectangular or larger angle to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
“If it weren’t, the robot wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot turn upwards or downwards, and even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which it can rotate its wheels and not exploit endless directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotational function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
“This device only needs to process the information every few seconds, and to act on the basis of this data.
It does not require the storage of information or the intuitive logic of previous manoeuvres, so it can work without interruption and with just a few dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even mega.”
It is the first step towards the development of new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than lithium-ion batteries.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of units with a GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to destination by avoiding the obstacles present in the route.
