The Frog in the Chicken
In America, life and health insurers, based on people’s medical purchase data, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription data of medicines depends in any case on the consent of the person concerned.
This program has to be in independent hands, otherwise it’s like entrusting the chicken to the fox,” writes the Washington Post, citing Richard Dick, the program’s author, to follow the prescriptions of medicines.
Insurers shall subordinate the insurance fee and the amount incurred in case of accidents to the health status of the potential customer and if they consider the risk to be too high they do not undertake insurance.
A long time ago the client had to undergo a medical visit and the contract was concluded only after the outcome of the exam.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the customer identification code you can easily get information from pharmacies about which medicines he has bought in the last year and a half, and hence the program shows which diseases he suffers and in which health conditions he is in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers this means that your blood fat level is invariably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
There are various versions of the program on the market, some also determine the risk multiplier, so the insurer does not remain much in addition to paperwork, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the contras is that some medicines can be used for multiple purposes, e.g., some compounds are useful against migraines or heatwaves, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from an insurance-commercial point of view, is valid as a risk-increasing factor, the first two not.
For the request and data processing companies have formed separately and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the patient's approval.
Now the authorities are obliged to do so even if they have not imposed fines for negligence so far.
Some companies have also recently processed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to drug consumption data in order to provide a more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to the data and in parallel controlling usage will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of Congress there is a bill that gives the authorities the authority to control the companies that specialize in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: that is why he has developed a program that connects the data transmission with the consent expressed by the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much refuse the approval because otherwise the insurers do not enter into the contract.
So eventually the chickens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
